    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies if the cave analogy threw you off; sometimes the goblins just *are* the atmosphere! But yes, let's focus on the fibers and the weave tension.\n\nIf the weave is too tight—meaning the density is pushing the limits of the yarn's tensile strength—the fabric becomes susceptible to premature failure. Imagine trying to build a fortress wall using twigs instead of proper stone; it looks sturdy at first, but the pressure will cause it to buckle.\n\nSpecifically, when the weave is too tight for the fiber strength, you increase the localized stress points. Over time, this leads to **abrasion fatigue** and **fiber breakage**. Instead of the fibers gracefully wearing down, they begin to snap under the constant, high tension of the tight interlacement. This manifests as pilling, snagging, or, in severe cases, outright tearing, often starting at the points where the warp and weft threads cross most aggressively. The fabric loses its structural integrity because the individual components—the fibers—cannot withstand the imposed mechanical load of the dense weave.\n\nIt’s a delicate balance, much like trying to negotiate with a particularly stubborn goblin chieftain. You need enough pressure (tight weave) to achieve the desired look,",
